snippet.title: 'The Hobbit': The most-pirated movie of 2013
snippet.description: Fans of Bilbo Baggins, Gandalf, and the Dwarves of Erebor download the film a whopping 8.4 million times making it No. 1 in the top 10 most pirated movies list.

snippet.title: Walt Disney, Sony Pictures test rentals of in-theater films
snippet.description: The companies allow customers in South Korea to rent films that are still playing in theaters, but it's unclear if the test will expand to other countries.

snippet.title: Digital movie sales climb 47 percent in 2013
snippet.description: While overall digital home entertainment spending remains fairly steady at $18.2 billion, digital movies sales shoot through the roof raking in $1.19 billion.

snippet.title: Oscars winners, losers jump in Amazon sales rankings
snippet.description: Volume 10 of host Seth MacFarlane's "Family Guy" jumped more than 3,000 percent on the site's bestseller list, while best picture winner "Argo" climbed five spots to No. 25.

snippet.title: The art of the guitar honored in three NYC shows
snippet.description: The Metropolitan Museum, Museum of Modern Art, and the Morrison Hotel Gallery all feature shows that honor the art of the guitar.

snippet.title: 2013 Infiniti G37
snippet.description: Due for an update, the 2013 Infiniti G37 relies on older tech under the hood and in the cabin, which might have been cutting-edge at launch but has become mostly average in the face of advances from the competition.

snippet.title: Washington Times and Mises.org release open-source projects
snippet.description: Enterprise IT is answering the call to contribute back to open-source projects.

snippet.title: Facebook open-sources real-time FriendFeed facet
snippet.description: Company makes real-time technology of new acquisition open source. Developers interested in incorporating Tornado into their Web service can do that now.

snippet.title: Cloud computing: How we got here
snippet.description: With roots in computer clustering and grid computing, the technology that first sprouted during the ASP era of the late 1990s is now the computing topic du jour.
